# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aush-reshteh
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aush-reshteh/abgoosht] Ābgoosht is usually made with lamb, chickpeas, white beans, onion, potatoes, tomatoes, turmeric, and dried lime.
[src:aush-reshteh/abgoosht] Other variations exist in the beans used, such as kidney beans and black-eyed peas.
[src:aush-reshteh/abgoosht] The ingredients are combined and cooked until done, at which point the dish is strained.
[src:aush-reshteh/abgoosht] The popular Azerbaijani dish piti is a variety of abgoosht and encompasses many similar dishes in the region.
[src:aush-reshteh/abgoosht] Assyrians of northwestern Iran, particularly surrounding Urmia, traditionally make abgoosht using beef, lime, kidney beans, and chickpeas, which is served in a lime broth with potatoes and eaten with onions and lavasha (an Assyrian bread) on the side.
[src:aush-reshteh/abgoosht] Assyrians typically make abgoosht in the winter.
[src:aush-reshteh/abgoosht] The regional pronunciation is "abgoosh", without the 't' (ܐܒܓܘܫ).
[src:aush-reshteh/abgoosht] A similar dish in Armenia is also called abgoosht.
[src:aush-reshteh/abgoosht] The difference is that in Armenia beef rather than lamb is used.
[src:aush-reshteh/abgoosht] Piti (or *putuk*) is a variation of abgoosht in the cuisines of the Caucasus and Central Asia.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] Acorn noodle soup may be made from acorns collected from red or white oak species and each oak species gives a distinct flavour.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] Ingredient labels do not list from which type of tree acorns are gathered, most likely owing to the large number of oak species and increasing oak hybridization (especially among white oak varieties), which makes it difficult to recognise and document each type of species.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] Evidence at Neolithic sites such as Amsa-dong in South Korea show acorns were part of the human diet.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] Acorns contain bitter tannins which would have been leached out to make the acorns edible.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] They were then ground into flour using a saddle quern and milling stone.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] It is unknown exactly where acorn noodles were first produced.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] However, Ogam village, Korea is well known for a long history of acorn cultivation.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] The village's location by the Namhangang River and its mountainous climate and landscape is conducive toward large-scale acorn cultivation.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] The village produces dozens of acorn-based foods, including *dotori kalguksoo* (acorn knife-cut noodles).
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] There are two varieties of acorn noodles: flour-based soba and starch-based vermicelli.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] Acorn vermicelli noodles or *dotori naengmyeon* (Korean: 냉면 도토리) are made from acorn starch and some combination of potato, rice, or arrowroot starch, wheat flour, and salt.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] The dried noodles resemble brown plastic threads about 1—1.2 mm in diameter.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] Cooked properly and typically eaten cold, acorn-based *naengmyeon* noodles have high elasticity and a chewy consistency.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] Acorn soba noodles, or, in Korean, *dotori guksu* (도토리국수), are made from acorn flour and a combination of grain-based flours such as buckwheat and corn, and salt.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] They are about as thick as spaghetti and are used in hot and cold dishes, such as *zaru soba*, in which boiled noodles are served cold with a dipping sauce.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] The Japanese version of these noodles, *donguri-men* (Japanese:どんぐり), typically has less acorn flour than the original Korean version.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] Raw acorn noodles are slightly coarser in cut and texture and more brittle than standard buckwheat soba noodles.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] Cooked acorn soba noodles are nuttier in flavor and slightly saltier than buckwheat noodles.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] They contain many antioxidants and could be considered an adaptogenic food.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] A common problem among Korean-manufactured products is that their ingredient labels are often not properly translated.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] Acorn starch is frequently mislabeled as acorn flour or acorn powder.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] In reality, acorn starch is essentially highly refined acorn flour, devoid of fiber, fat, and almost all nutrition.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] While the acorn itself does indeed contain acorn starch, that starch is not highly refined.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] Acorn starch, in contrast, is extracted from the meat of the kernel using a wet process and then dehydrated.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] The heart, or germ, of the kernel is removed and used for producing acorn oil, which is comparable in flavor and quality to olive oil.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] The hull is separated from the kernel meat, and the starch is extracted from the kernel meat.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] It might be more accurate to use the term "acorn meal", although a meal is a coarser, less refined version of flour.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] Both flour- and starch-based acorn noodles are available in upscale Korean markets.
[src:aush-reshteh/acorn-noodle-soup] A few Japanese markets also carry acorn soba noodles, but in general, acorn soba noodles are difficult to find.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] The cuisine of Afghanistan is *halal* and uses various herbs and spices including coriander, mint, dill, cumin, cardamom and turmeric as well as locally-grown saffron.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Afghan dishes are typically mild in flavor.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] A variety of rice dishes known locally as 'palao' are prepared with various fruits, nuts and legumes, and combine sweet and sour flavors central to Afghan cuisine.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Dumpling and noodle dishes, meat and vegetable stews, legumes, and kebab dishes make up the bulk of Afghan cuisine.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Rice is a core staple food in Afghan cuisine and the most important part of any meal.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Challow, or white rice cooked with mild spices, is served mainly with *qormas* (*korma*: stews or casseroles).
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Palaw is cooked similarly to challow, but a combination of meat, stock, *qorma*, and herbs are also mixed in before baking, resulting in the elaborate colors, flavors, and aromas from which the rice got its name.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Sometimes caramelized sugar is used to give the rice a rich brown color.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Afghan bread is flat and cooked in a tanoor or tandoor (a vertical ground clay oven).
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] The bread is slapped onto a stone wall to cook.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Tabakhai is a flatbread cooked on a flat upside-down pan.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Known under the name *khameerbob* and often eaten as dumplings, they are rarely served at large gatherings, such as weddings.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] They are instead served on special occasions at home.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Qormah (also spelled "korma" or "qorma") is an onion- and tomato-based stew or casserole usually served with challow rice.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] First, onion is caramelized, for a richly colored stew.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Then tomato is added, along with a variety of fruits, spices, and vegetables, depending on the recipe.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] The main ingredient, which can be meat or other vegetables, is added last.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Afghan kabob is most often found in restaurants and at outdoor street vendor stalls.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Most of the time, it contains lamb meat.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Kabob is made with naan instead of rice.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Customers have the option to sprinkle sumac or *ghore angoor* (dried ground sour grapes) on their kabob.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Pieces of fat from the sheep's tail (*jijeq*) are usually added to the skewers to add extra flavor.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Traditional Afghan kabobs are made with onion juice, lemon, yoghurt, black pepper and sometimes saffron for chicken.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Other popular kabobs include the lamb chop, ribs, *kofta* (ground beef), and chicken.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Chapli kebab, a specialty of eastern Afghanistan, is a patty of minced beef.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] It is a popular barbecue meal in Afghanistan.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] It is prepared flat and round and served with naan.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] The original recipe of chapli kabob dictates a half-meat, half-flour mixture which renders it lighter in taste and less expensive.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] This type of kabob contains herbs and sometimes chilli.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Afghan chicken or *murgh-e* is a classic example of one of the most famous dishes of Afghanistan.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Chicken dishes are usually found in restaurants and at outdoor street vendor stalls.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Unlike in the Indian cooking style, chicken in Afghan cuisine is often used with the intention that it be *halal*.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Cream, butter, and curd are customary ingredients in all chicken recipes, whether served as an appetizer or a main course.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] As a dessert after a meal, most Afghans generally eat fresh fruit.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] For snacks, they may drink tea with something sweet like cakes, cookies or pastries.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] On occasions, they also eat dried fruits which are widely available in every Afghan market.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Chai is tea in Afghanistan, which can either be green or black.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] It is consumed at all times, especially a short time after finishing a meal or with guests during any social gathering.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Most people drink green tea with no sugar.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Doogh (also known by some Afghans as *shomleh* or *shlombeh*) is a cold drink made by mixing water with yogurt and then adding fresh or dried mint.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Some variations of doogh include the addition of crushed or diced cucumber chunks.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] It is the second most widely consumed drink in Afghanistan (the first being tea), especially during lunchtime in summer.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Doogh can be found at almost every Afghan grocery store and is served in restaurants.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] While Afghans have a common cuisine, certain ethnicities form sub-variations of it.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Pashtuns are the largest ethnic group of Afghanistan, constituting about 42% of the country's total population.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] A major dish in Pashtun culture are rosh (cooked lamb and mutton with no spices) and sohbat, found at traditional gatherings and events.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Other major Pashtun dishes include lamb-skewered *sajji* and *chapli kebab*.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] The name *dampukht* stands for steamed meat, and *khaddi kebab* is the Afghan shashlik, which is grilled on an open fire, on a spit.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Although it differs between regions, Pashtun cuisine is meat-heavy and often includes caramelized rice.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] For example, the dish known as *bolani* in the north and east is often called *borogyen* in the south and west of Afghanistan.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Common summer beverages include *shlombeh*, a drink consisting of liquid yogurt, mint, and cucumber.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] *Sher yakh* is a sweet ice-like product.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] The Hazara people in central Afghanistan (in the region of Hazarajat) and western Pakistan (Balochistan province) have their own fare.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] The Hazaragi cuisine shares some similarities with neighboring regional cuisines, so it is mainly influenced by Central Asian, Persian, and South Asian cooking.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] However, cooking methods vary in some of the dishes of these neighboring cuisines.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Traditionally, dinners are served on a tablecloth on the floor, which is called the *dastarkhan*.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Meals are normally eaten with the right hand.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] After a meal, tea with dessert is served.
[src:aush-reshteh/afghan-cuisine] Serving tea and white sugared almonds (called *nuql*) is customary during Afghan festivals.
[src:aush-reshteh/albaloo-polo] The dish can also be served as a type of scorched rice, known as **albaloo polow ba tahdiq maast** (آلبالوپلو با ته‌دیگ ماست), a specialty rice dish with a hardened bottom layer.
[src:aush-reshteh/albaloo-polo] The herbs and spices used in this variation of polo vary, but typically include advieh, and saffron.
[src:aush-reshteh/aragh-sagi] Since the Iranian revolution in 1979, alcohol is illegal in Iran.
[src:aush-reshteh/aragh-sagi] As such, homemade Aragh sagi in Iran is produced illegally.
[src:aush-reshteh/aragh-sagi] It is usually produced in homes from fermented raisins.
[src:aush-reshteh/aragh-sagi] Its production and possession by ordinary citizens is illegal in Iran (which is the case for all alcoholic beverages in Iran).
[src:aush-reshteh/aragh-sagi] Prior to 1979 revolution in Iran, this product had been produced traditionally in several cities, such as Yazd.
[src:aush-reshteh/aragh-sagi] Since it was outlawed after 1979, it became a black market and underground business.
[src:aush-reshteh/aragh-sagi] Today, aragh sagi is widely considered a cheap alcoholic beverage that consumers choose due to lack of other available alternative options.
[src:aush-reshteh/aragh-sagi] Cyrus Premium Arak is produced by Cyrus Company in the Netherlands.
[src:aush-reshteh/aragh-sagi] Cyrus Arak Saggi is made in small batches using copper pot stills.
[src:aush-reshteh/aragh-sagi] Fermented raisins are distilled to create a clear arak with an alcohol content of 40%.
[src:aush-reshteh/aragh-sagi] Raisins are sourced from Iran and Turkey.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] The preparation of meat, fish, and vegetable dishes in an Armenian kitchen often requires stuffing, frothing, and puréeing.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Lamb, eggplant, and bread (lavash) are basic features of Armenian cuisine.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Armenians traditionally prefer cracked wheat to maize and rice.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] The flavor of the food often relies on the quality and freshness of the ingredients rather than on excessive use of spices.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Fresh herbs are used extensively, both in the food and as accompaniments.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Dried herbs are used in the winter when fresh herbs are not available.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Wheat is the primary grain and is found in a variety of forms, such as whole wheat, shelled wheat, bulgur (parboiled cracked wheat), semolina, farina, and flour.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Historically, rice was used mostly in the cities and in certain rice-growing areas (such as Marash and the region around Yerevan).
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Legumes are used liberally, especially chick peas, lentils, white beans, and kidney beans.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Nuts are used both for texture and to add nutrition to Lenten dishes.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Of primary usage are not only walnuts, almonds, and pine nuts, but also hazelnuts, pistachios (in Cilicia), and nuts from regional trees.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Fresh and dried fruit are used both as main ingredients and as sour agents.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] As main ingredients, the following fruits are used: apricots (fresh and dried), quince, melons, and others.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] As sour agents, the following fruits are used: sumac berries (in dried, powdered form), sour grapes, plums (either sour or dried), pomegranate, apricots, cherries (especially sour cherries), and lemons.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] In addition to grape leaves, cabbage leaves, chard, beet leaves, radish leaves, strawberry leaves, and others are also stuffed.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] A typical meal in an Armenian household might consist of bread, butter, buttermilk, cheese, fresh and pickled vegetables, and radishes.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Lunch might include a vegetable or meatball soup with sour milk.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Lamb, yogurt, eggplant and bread are basic features of the Armenian cuisine, but there are some regional differences.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] In Soviet cookbooks the Armenian cuisine is always stated to be the oldest of Transcaucasia and one of the oldest in all of Asia.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Armenian dishes make use of cracked wheat, while Georgian variations use maize.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Armenian cuisine also makes use of mixed flours made from wheat, potato and maize, which produces flavors that are difficult to replicate.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Archaeologists have found traces of barley, grapes, lentils, peas, plums, sesame, and wheat during excavations of the Erebuni Fortress in Yerevan.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Herbs are used copiously in Armenian cuisine, and Armenian desserts are often flavored with rose water, orange flower water and honey.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Salads are a staple of the Armenian diet, along with various yogurt soups and lamb stews, which sometimes include apricots.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Pomegranate juice is a popular beverage.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Murat Belge wrote that both Armenian and Iranian cuisine have meat and fruit dishes, where meat is cooked together with fruits like quince and plums, which are uncommon in Ottoman cuisine.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Mezes made with chickpeas, lentils, beans and eggplant play a role in Armenian cuisine, often served with traditional lavash bread.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Lavash may also be used as a wrap for various combinations of fried meat, vegetables, cheese and herbs.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Armenian cuisine also features filled pastry called *boereg*, various types of sausages, toasted pumpkin seeds, pistachios, pine nuts, *basturma* (seasoned pressed beef), and dolma.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Cinnamon is a common spice in Armenian cuisine; it is sprinkled on soups, breads, desserts and sometimes fish.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] Salads are served with a lemon-cinnamon dressing alongside as an accompaniment to meat kebabs.
[src:aush-reshteh/armenian-cuisine] In a survey of Armenian-American cuisine, ginger was rated an important spice.
[src:aush-reshteh/aush-reshteh] There are more than 50 types of thick soup (ash) in Iranian cooking, this being one of the more common types.
[src:aush-reshteh/aush-reshteh] The ingredients used are reshteh (thin noodles), kashk (a whey-like, fermented dairy product), herbs such as parsley, spinach, dill, spring onion ends and sometimes coriander, chickpeas, black-eye beans, lentils, onions, flour, dried mint, garlic, oil, salt, and black pepper.
[src:aush-reshteh/aush-reshteh] Common garnishes include fried onion and fried garlic.
[src:aush-reshteh/aush-reshteh] Aush reshteh is traditionally vegetarian but can easily be made vegan by omitting the kashk; alternatively, meat can be added.
[src:aush-reshteh/aush-reshteh] Ash reshteh has its origins in the distant past.
[src:aush-reshteh/aush-reshteh] By 500 A.D., noodles were added to the dish.
[src:aush-reshteh/aush-reshteh] It is cooked most often in autumn and winter.
[src:aush-reshteh/aush-reshteh] Traditionally, aush reshteh is served at special Iranian events like Nowruz or Sizdah Be-dar, or during wintertime.
[src:aush-reshteh/aush-reshteh] The noodles are supposed to symbolize good fortune for the new year.
